@NODE "Introduction" "Introduction"
@TOC "MAIN"

Introduction
************

MergeRec updates your local copy of the Aminet "INDEX" file by merging
the recent uploads from a "RECENT" file, "aminet-weekly" or "aminet-daily"
mailing list.

The index produced by MergeRec is sorted, and has the 'Age' column correctly
updated.

With MergeRec you can use the RECENT file downloaded from a ftp site, or the
e-mailed aminet-weekly/daily recent uploads list, without manually removing
the extraneous lines (header and/or other messages) in the input file.
MergeRec automatically extract the RECENT list(s) from your mailbox file.
It accepts multiple recents (daily/weekly) and it don't cares if the lines
end with LF or CR+LF.

You can also save (or append) the extracted RECENT to a file. This option
is useful if you want to use GadMget or share the file with users if you
run a bbs, for example.

Another option compares the RECENT file to your INDEX, and saves to a file
those entries that are really new uploads. This option is useful especially
for the aminet-daily mailing list, that frequently contains entries that
were 'recent' a few days before.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Notes" "Important notes"
@TOC "MAIN"

Important notes
***************

If you download the RECENT files directly from an Aminet site, be sure to
get them after no more than 7 days, otherwise you lost some new-entries.
(the RECENT file contains only the last 7 days uploads). 

This problem do not arise if you subscribe to aminet-weekly. In this
case it is important that the "Recent uploads" list is not modified by
the mail program you (or your provider) have. That is: @{B}NO justification@{UB}
of lines, and @{B}NO line breaks@{UB} for lines 80 char long. Otherwise you must
manually restore the original format of the file...

The program doesn't work with the regular INDEX (found in pub/aminet),
because it hasn't the age column. Use the file pub/aminet/info/index/INDEX

The index produced by the program contains more files than the original
Aminet index. Infact, when a program with the version number included in
its name is released, usually older versions are deleted from Aminet.
But since the RECENT file contains only the new uploads, and not a list
of deleted files, MergeRec can't know what entries must be deleted.
For this reason, it is advisable after some time (for example 6 months)
to replace the updated index with an original aminet index.

@{FG "Shine"}ATTENTION MergeRec v1.1 users:@{FG "Text"} the template is changed, see @{"Usage" LINK "Usage"}


@ENDNODE

@NODE "Requirements" "System requirements"
@TOC "MAIN"

System requirements
*******************

A Pentium 900 MHz processor with at least 32 MB RAM is required to load
this program. You need more RAM and a 2.4 GHz P6 processor (that one
with a microwave oven as a clock generator) if you want also to run it.
Oops!... :-)

MergeRec needs Kickstart V37 (WorkBench 2.04) or higher.

Obviously, you need a HD to store the Aminet index file (1.7 MB now!).
A great amount of RAM is not required, since the merge process store
in RAM only the recent list (20-30KB).
   
On an A1200 with 020/28MHz 4MB fast (Blizzard1220/4) it tooks about 95
seconds to update the 1.7 MB index (all files in the hard disk).
I know it's slow, but you'll use it once a week! And with the Amiga the
multitasking is not a new discover!

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Usage" "Usage"
@TOC "MAIN"

Usage
*****

MergeRec can be used only from Shell. @{FG "Shine"}Template is changed from v1.1@{FG "Text"}
See also: @{"examples" LINK "Examples"} and @{"important notes" LINK "Notes"}. The command template is:
(don't panic, see the examples!)


  MergeRec RECENTFILE/A, OLDINDEX, NEWINDEX, REP=REPLACE/S, STDOUT/S, 
           SR=SAVERECENT/K, APP=APPEND/S, STAT=STATISTICS/S, NOSORT/S,
           NRH=NORECHEADER/S, SN=SAVENEWS/K, NNH=NONEWSHEADER/S

Where:

  @{" RECENTFILE/A       " LINK "REC"}  An Aminet RECENT file or weekly/daily mail-list.
  @{" OLDINDEX           " LINK "OLD"}  The local copy of an Aminet info/index/INDEX file.
  @{" NEWINDEX           " LINK "NEW"}  File to store the new index file.

  @{" REP=REPLACE/S      " LINK "REP"}  Switch: replace old index with the new.
  @{" STDOUT/S           " LINK "STDOUT"}  Switch: redirect the new index to standard output.

  @{" SR=SAVERECENT/K    " LINK "SR"}  File to store (or append) the preprocessed recents.
  @{" APP=APPEND/S       " LINK "APP"}  Switch: append recents to the end of SAVERECENT file.
  @{" STAT=STATISTICS/S  " LINK "STAT"}  Switch: add also statistics to SAVERECENT file.
  @{" NOSORT/S           " LINK "NOSORT"}  Switch: do no sort/merge the SAVERECENT file.
  @{" NRH=NORECHEADER/S  " LINK "NRH"}  Switch: do not put header in the SAVERECENT file.

  @{" SN=SAVENEWS/K      " LINK "SN"}  File to store only the really new uploads (sorted).
  @{" NNH=NONEWSHEADER/S " LINK "NNH"}  Switch: do not put header in the SAVENEWS file.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "REC" "RECENTFILE/A"
@TOC "MAIN"

RECENTFILE/A

   An Aminet RECENT file, either downloaded from an Aminet site or received
   by e-mail from wuarchive listserver (aminet-weekly or aminet-daily).

   You can give a file that contains one ore more messages of your mailbox:
   MergeRec exctracts EVERY aminet-recent list it encounters in the file
   (don't cares if lines end with LF or CR+LF). All the recent found are
   merged and sorted together (removing also the duplicates).
  
   If you want not to merge/sort multiple recents in the SAVERECENT file, use
   the @{"NOSORT" LINK "NOSORT"} switch.

   @{B}IMPORTANT NOTES:@{UB} 
   * the lines of the file must not be justified or broken by the mail
     reader, otherwise the program won't work.
   * if multiple recent are present in the input file, the program treats
     them as a single upload list with the upload date taken from the last
     recent found. For this reason, if the first and last recent are more
     than a week apart, the older entries gets an incorrect age (younger).

   This argument is always required.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "OLD" "OLDINDEX"
@TOC "MAIN"
   
OLDINDEX

   The local copy of an Aminet info/index/INDEX file.

   The program warns you if the index file is more than a week older than
   the recent list.

   @{B}WARNING:@{UB} The regular INDEX file (pub/aminet/INDEX) will NOT work!
   Use the file pub/aminet/info/index/INDEX because it contains a
   'weeks old' column.

   This argument is required if the @{"SAVERECENT" LINK "SR"} option is not used.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "NEW" "NEWINDEX"
@TOC "MAIN"

NEWINDEX

   Filename of the new index file (output). 

   If you want to replace the old index, instead of creating a new one,
   use the @{"REPLACE" LINK "REP"} option, and do not give the NEWINDEX name.
   
   If you want only to view the new index without saving it, use the
   @{"STDOUT" LINK "STDOUT"} option (redirects the output to the Shell).

   This argument is required if @{"SAVERECENT" LINK "SR"} and @{"SAVENEWS" LINK "SN"} options are not
   used.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "REP" "REPLACE/S"
@TOC "MAIN"

REP=REPLACE/S

   Switch: if set, then the @{"OLDINDEX" LINK "OLD"} is deleted and replaced by the new.

   How it works: First the program creates a new temporary file with the
   same name (and in the same directory) of OLDINDEX, but with a ".new"
   suffix.  When the new index is ready, the old is deleted, and the new
   renamed as the old.

   If something wrong happens while the new index is constructed, like a
   system crash (as the Murphy's laws foresee...), the old index is still
   here.

   @{B}Notes:@{UB}
   * You must have the space in the directory for both old and new indexes.
   * @{"REPLACE" LINK "REP"}, @{"STDOUT" LINK "STDOUT"} and @{"NEWINDEX" LINK "NEW"} are mutually exclusive, you can use
     only one of them.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "STDOUT" "STDOUT/S"
@TOC "MAIN"

STDOUT/S

   Switch: if set, then the program redirects the new index to standard
   output (Shell).

   @{B}Note:@{UB} @{"STDOUT" LINK "STDOUT"}, @{"REPLACE" LINK "REP"}, and @{"NEWINDEX" LINK "NEW"} are mutually exclusive, you can
         use only one of them.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "SR" "SAVERECENT/K"
@TOC "MAIN"

SR=SAVERECENT/K

   This is an optional filename used to store (or append) the RECENT
   or aminet-weekly/daily list(s) extracted from the @{"RECENTFILE" LINK "REC"}.

   By default only the recent upload list (with the header) is saved,
   but you can also include the most downloaded and highest rated
   programs using the @{"STAT" LINK "STAT"} option.

   The recent list(s) can be appended to the SAVERECENT file using the
   @{"APP" LINK "APP"} option.

   The entries in the RECENTFILE are sorted by default, and multiple
   lists are merged together. Use @{"NOSORT" LINK "NOSORT"} to avoid this.
   
   The SAVERECENT file cointains the standard header, unless you use
   the @{"NRH" LINK "NRH"} option.

   @{B}Note:@{UB} this option requires the keyword and a filename: 
        "SAVERECENT file" or "SR file".
@ENDNODE

@NODE "APP" "APPEND/S"
@TOC "MAIN"

APP=APPEND/S

   Switch: if set, then the recent list extracted from @{"RECENTFILE" LINK "REC"} is
   appended to the end of the @{"SAVERECENT" LINK "SR"} file (that must already exists).

   This option is significant only if the @{"SAVERECENT" LINK "SR"} option is set.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "STAT" "STATISTICS/S"
@TOC "MAIN"

STAT=STATISTICS/S

   Switch: if set, then the @{"SAVERECENT" LINK "SR"} file contains the aminet-weekly
   statistics (most downloaded files and highest rated programs).
   Otherwise it reports only the recent uploads.

   This option requires the @{"SAVERECENT" LINK "SR"} and @{"NOSORT" LINK "NOSORT"} options to be active.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "NOSORT" "NOSORT/S"
@TOC "MAIN"

NOSORT/S

   Switch: if set disables the sorting and merging of multiple recent lists
   in the @{"SAVERECENT" LINK "SR"} file.

   This option is significant only if the @{"SAVERECENT" LINK "SR"} option is set.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "NRH" "NORECHEADER/S"
@TOC "MAIN"

NRH=NORECHEADER/S

   Switch: if set the the @{"SAVERECENT" LINK "SR"} file don't have header. 
   This option may be useful for an external processing of that file.

   This option is significant only if the @{"SAVERECENT" LINK "SR"} option is set.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "SN" "SAVENEWS/K"
@TOC "MAIN"

SN=SAVENEWS/K

   This is an optional filename used to store ONLY the recent entries
   (extracted from @{"RECENTFILE" LINK "REC"}) that are @{B}really@{UB} new uploads.

   In practice, one program is excluded from this file if:
   (it's already present in the OLDINDEX) AND (have the same readme part)
   AND (has an age of 0 or 1 weeks).

   The reason for this option is that frequently the aminet-daily list
   contains entries that were "recent" a few day before.

   See also @{"Why SAVENEWS?" LINK "Examples" 55}.

   The SAVENEWS file cointains the standard header, unless you use
   the @{"NNH" LINK "NNH"} option.

   @{B}Notes:@{UB}
   * this option requires the keyword and a filename: "SAVENEWS file"
     or "SN file".
   * You must give also an index (@{"OLDINDEX" LINK "OLD"} argument)

@ENDNODE

@NODE "NNH" "NONEWSHEADER/S"
@TOC "MAIN"

NNH=NONEWSHEADER/S

   Switch: if set the the @{"SAVENEWS" LINK "SN"} file don't have header. 
   This option may be useful for an external processing of that file.

   This option is significant only if the @{"SAVENEWS" LINK "SN"} option is set.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Examples" "Examples"
@TOC "MAIN"

Examples
********

I've put two small example files, so you can experiment with MergeRec.
@{"Index" LINK "examples/index/main"} is a very small version of an Aminet INDEX, while @{"mbox_rec" LINK "examples/mbox_rec/main"} is
a short demo of the contents of a mailbox with two daily and one weekly
list, together with other mails.

MergeRec treats this three recents like one with date 21-Jan-96, and
since it has a difference of more than a week with the index file, 
MergeRec warns you.

In the directory "examples" you can also find the outputs of the program:
@{"new_index" LINK "examples/new_index/main"} and @{"saved_rec" LINK "examples/saved_rec/main"} (the recent list extracted from @{"mbox_rec" LINK "examples/mbox_rec/main"}).


Examples of normal usage of MergeRec:
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
*  MergeRec @{"mbox_rec" LINK "REC"} @{"index" LINK "OLD"} @{"REP" LINK "REP"}

   Updates "index" with "mbox_rec", replacing the old index.
   A temporary file "index.new" is used. Note that the old index is
   deleted only after the completion of the new, so if something goes
   wrong (always remember Murphy's laws..), the old index remains
   intact (and you can find the new as "index.new").
   
   If you don't want to overwrite the old index, simply give as third argument
   the name of the new index:

*  MergeRec @{"mbox_rec" LINK "REC"} @{"index" LINK "OLD"} @{"mynewindex" LINK "NEW"}

   Merges the aminet-weekly contained in @{"mbox_rec" LINK "examples/mbox_rec/main"} with @{"index" LINK "examples/index/main"}, and
   writes the new index to @{"mynewindex" LINK "examples/new_index/main"}

*  MergeRec @{"mbox_rec" LINK "REC"} @{"index" LINK "OLD"} @{"REP" LINK "REP"} @{"SR ram:whatsnew" LINK "SR"}
 
   Like the first example, but also writes the recent lists (sorted and merged)
   extracted from @{"mbox_rec" LINK "examples/mbox_rec/main"} to @{"ram:whatsnew" LINK "examples/saved_rec/main"}


Examples of advanced usage of MergeRec:
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
*  MergeRec @{"mbox_rec" LINK "REC"} @{"SR recent1" LINK "SR"}

   Do not update any index, only writes the recent list extracted
   from the mailbox file @{"mbox_rec" LINK "examples/mbox_rec/main"} to @{"recent1" LINK "examples/saved_rec/main"}, merging and sorting
   the entries found.
   
*  MergeRec @{"mbox_rec" LINK "REC"} @{"index" LINK "OLD"} @{"SN news" LINK "SN"}

   Extracts from the recent list only those entries that are really new
   uploads (entries already present in the index are rejected if their
   readme part isn't changed and their age is 0 or 1 week), and writes
   them to "news". The index is not updated.
  
   And now a very complicated example...
 
*  MergeRec @{"mbox_rec" LINK "REC"} @{"index" LINK "OLD"} @{"REP" LINK "REP"} @{"SR work:allrecents" LINK "SR"} @{"APP" LINK "APP"} @{"STAT" LINK "STAT"} @{"NOSORT" LINK "NOSORT"} @{"SN news" LINK "SN"} @{"NNH" LINK "NNH"}

   Updates the index (replacing the old), appends the recent list to
   "work:allrecents", adding also the statistical charts (most downloaded
   and rated programs) without merging/sorting multiple lists, and saves
   the really new uploads to "news", stripping the header.
   Note that you can use the @{"APP" LINK "APP"} option only if the file "work:allrecents"
   already exists. So, the first time you must create it without the @{"APP" LINK "APP"}
   option.


Why SAVENEWS option?
********************

This option, requested by Johan Torin, it is useful if you have for example
a bbs with full mirror of Aminet, and want to update daily your mirror with
the recent uploads. Since frequently the aminet-daily list contains entries
found a few days before (duplicates), if you use the SAVERECENT file to
auto download the files from an Aminet site, you may download some files
that you already have. With SAVENEWS option you can avoid this situation,
using the following procedure:

- MergeRec mailbox myindex SAVERECENT recent SAVENEWS downloadlist NNH
  Read the recent files from mailbox, saves all of them to "recent", and
  only the new entries to "downloadlist" (without header). The index is
  not updated.

- Use some fancy download script/program to fetch the files listed in
  "downloadlist" from AmiNet. For each NOT successful download, delete
  the coresponding line from the "downloadlist" file.

- MergeRec downloadlist myindex REPLACE
  Updates the index with the downloaded files.

The SAVENEWS file has a different @{"header" LINK "Headers" 28} (New aminet uploads on...).

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Suggestions" "Other useful programs"
@TOC "MAIN"

Other useful programs
*********************

If you want to search the index without loading it in your editor (to
save RAM), I suggest the use of @{B}FlashFind@{UB} by Frank Würkner. It's VERY
fast (more than 10 times faster than "search").
If you add an alias like this: 

   alias af "flashfind work:docs/lists/aminetindex "

in the shell-startup, you can easily make a search from a shell by typing:

   af name

The FlashFind program can be found on Aminet. The new 1.2 release is
more powerful and faster than v1.1.
(util/cli/FlashFind1.2.lha  12K)


Another useful program for the recent files is @{B}GadMget@{UB} by Jeremy Friesner.
GadMget lets you select the files you want to download by clicking on them
in a listview gadget. The program then automagically creates a file with
the mgets and cd commands needed to download the files by ftp.
GadMget can be found on Aminet (util/misc/GadMget2.05.lha   93K)

@ENDNODE

